Introduction to X Macros
========================

Iterate over a non-coninuous enum
---------------------------------
Imagine you have an enum type that has not continuous values but you want to iterate over the values.

    :::C
    typedef enum
    {
      COLOR_RED   = 0x0000ff,
      COLOR_GREEN = 0x00ff00,
      COLOR_BLUE  = 0xff0000
    } colors_t;
    
Instead of writing it as usual we will do something different:

    :::C
    // file: colors.xdef
    COLOR(COLOR_RED,   0x0000ff)
    COLOR(COLOR_GREEN, 0x00ff00)
    COLOR(COLOR_BLUE,  0xff0000)

This macro calls are written to a file with the ending xdef. Some use the ending def, but this ending is used as linker definition file on Windows. I have also seen the ending g.

    :::C
    // main.c
    typedef enum
    {
      #define COLOR(id, value) id = value,
      #include "colors.xdef"
      #undef COLOR
    } colors_t;
    
    typedef enum
    {
      #define COLOR(id, value) id##_ID,
      #include "colors.xdef"
      COLORS_NUM
      #undef COLOR
    } colors_id_t;
    
    int main()
    {
      int i = 0;
      for (i, i < COLORS_NUM, ++i)
      {
        printf("%i\n");
      }
      
      return 0;
    }

